  <h2>What is a CPU?</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>CPU</strong> stands for <strong>Central Processing Unit</strong>. It is the most important chip inside your computer — often called the <em>brain</em> of the computer. Every time you click, type, or watch a video, the CPU is hard at work!
  </p>

  <h2>What Does the CPU Do?</h2>
  <p>The CPU follows a simple three-step cycle over and over, billions of times per second:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>📥 <strong>Fetch</strong> — Gets the next instruction from memory.</li>
    <li>🔍 <strong>Decode</strong> — Figures out what the instruction means.</li>
    <li>⚡ <strong>Execute</strong> — Carries out the instruction.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How Fast is a CPU?</h2>
  <p>
    Modern CPUs run at speeds measured in <strong>GHz (Gigahertz)</strong>. A 3 GHz CPU can perform 3 <em>billion</em> cycles per second. That's faster than you can blink your eye!
  </p>

  <h2>CPU Cores</h2>
  <p>
    Modern CPUs have multiple <strong>cores</strong> — think of each core as a separate brain. A <em>quad-core</em> CPU has 4 cores and can work on 4 tasks at the same time!
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    Imagine the CPU is a chef. A single-core CPU is one chef doing all the cooking. A quad-core CPU is four chefs cooking different dishes at the same time — much faster!
  </blockquote>

